         <abstract>
            <p>This paper examines the "term structure" of options' implied volatilities, using data on S&amp;P 100 index options. Because implied volatility is strongly mean reverting, the implied volatility on a longer maturity option should move by less than one percent in response to a one percent move in the implied volatility of a shorter maturity option. Empirically, this elasticity turns out to be larger than suggested by rational expectations theory--long-maturity options tend to "overreact" to changes in the implied volatility of short-maturity options.</p>
         </abstract>
